ref: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.203, p.193 (1973)
title: A Study of 30 MeV Proton Inelastic Scattering from Isotopes of Molybdenum and Zinc.

x4freetext: A Study of 30 MeV Proton Inelastic Scattering from
North East London Polytechnic, Stratford, UK
and King`s College, The Strand, London, UK.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.203, p.193 (1973)

x4freetext: The Zinc Targets were Rolled Self-Supporting Metal
Foils of Nominal Thicknesses 5 and 40 mg/cm**2.
The Molybdenum Targets were Self-Supporting 20 mg/cm**2
The Thicker Targets were Used Mainly For the Analyzing
The Main Impurities in Each Target were Other Isotopes
Of the Same Metal,Except For the Melinex-Based Target
Which Contributed Scattering Effects from Carbon and
Oxygen.Isotopic Impurities Comprised About 4% of the
Zn-66 Target, 3% of the Mo-96, 2% of the Mo-92 and
Mo-100 and 1% of the Zn-64 and Zn-68.
An Acoustic Spark Chamber Mounted in the
Focal Plane of the Magnet was Used As a
The Energy Resolution, Over the Angular Range Covered,
Averaged Approx. 100 KeV For the Cross Sections and

x4codes.hlp: Rutherford Appleton Laboratory, Chilton, England, United Kingdom

x4freetext: Cross Section Errors are Generally of the Order of 3%
To 5% While Analyzing Power Errors Range from About
0.03 at Forward Angles to About 0.1 at Backward Angles.
All Data are Uncorrected For the Angular Spread of the
Scattered Protons.This was Approx. O.6 Degree For the
Cross Section and Approx. 1.1 Degree For the Analyzing
Powers and is Due Mainly to the Aperture Defining Slits
.The Error was Mainly Due to Variation of
Energy with Penetration Into the Target and to the
Uncertainty in the Incident Beam Energy.
